The explanation of what is being compared is stored in columns where average diameter of Neuron1 and Neuroun2 is compared with each other for Hypothesis Testing The t Value for average_daimeter = -1.19 (for this Negative value seems fine as we compare the distance from 0 in this case the direction does not matter) The P-value is used to represent whether the outcome od a hypothesis test is statistically significant enough to be able to reject Null Hyphothesis. since, The P value is 0.231, which is greather than alpha = 0.01(Level of significance) in our case We do not reject the null hypothesis. and if we see other values we are able to observe the all the P-values which we got are greter than 0.01 which means there is difference in the properties while we can see p values are greater than threshold. H0: The properties of neuron 1 and neuron 2 are similar 1 = 2 H1: The properties of neuron 1 and neuron 2 are not similar 1 2 in our case we got H0 the null hypothesis.

Correlation is that it is used to check the relationship strength between the two variables, i.e if we change the value in one variable the correlation table will shows the level by which there will be a change in the second variable. Pearson coefficient correlation is used to measure the correlation for the linear data. The coefficient's value lie between -1 and 1. Where the value between 0 and 1 signifies positive correlation and value between -1 and 0 signifies negative correlation. Whereas, the value of 0 signifies no correlation.

In this we divided the data into predictor variable and target variable, As per question we had 19 predictors and 1 target variable for the linear regression model , with target beinf the Total surface
For this question we divided predictors and target variable with Iloc and in order to standardize the data we used Sk learn's standard scaler.

AIC

The Akaike information criterion (AIC) is a mathematical method for evaluating how well a model fits the data it was generated from
AIC is used to compare different possible models and determine which one is the best fit for the data.
AIC is calculated from:the number of independent variables used to build the model. The maximum likelihood estimate of the model (how well the model reproduces the data).
BIC has been widely used for model identification in time series and linear regression
BIC is always higher than AIC
The Bayesian probability (BIC) means that if a selection of candidate models includes a true model for the dataset, then the probability that BIC will select the true model increases with the size of the training dataset.
for this model we use 19 predictors and below are the AIC and BIC scores for the same we can see that as the dimensions are (columns,predictors) are more and as AIC score does consider this factor we have a score of ~ 79 with normal regression without any Bagging or Bossting method for feature selection
for this model we use 19 predictors and below are the AIC and BIC scores for the same we can see that as the dimensions are (columns,predictors) are more and as BIC score of ~ 80 with normal regression without any Bagging or Bossting method for feature selection

Forward selection typically begins with only an intercept. One tests the various variables that may be relevant, and the best variablewhere best is determined by some pre-determined criteriais added to the model

The criterion used to determine which variable goes in when are varied. You could be attempting to find the lowest score under cross validation, the lowest p-value, or any of a number of other tests or measures of accuracy.

Suppose that you have a dataset in which you want to discover groups, or clusters, that share certain characteristics. There are various unsupervised machine learning techniques that can be used to do this. As we've seen in other blogs, K-means clustering can be used if you have good data or small data
But in both cases, the clusters need to be separated. Or you may need to configure the number of clusters in advance.
Mean Shift clustering, a clustering approach for discovering "blobs in a smooth density of samples". That is, precisely what you want - discovering clusters if your data is not separated without configuring the number of clusters.
This is what the Mean Shift algorithm for clustering does. It looks at the "mode" of the density, and where it is highest, and will iteratively shift points in the plot towards the closest mode
with this we can find out the clusters where there is highest density
unlike k means this works good on small data
